s, which is interesting. I’ll need to clarify how optional data works with readObject, especially since ObjectInputStream reads field values before that.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Clarifying serialization behaviors**\\n\\nI'm diving into how a serializable class descriptor handles fields. The SC_WRITE_METHOD format starts with field values, followed by optional data, but since the stream descriptor has 0 fields, there are no values to read. This situation gets tricky when serializing JDKDSAPrivateKey, which includes 3 fields. If a custom writeObject is used without calling defaultWriteObject, the field values won’t be there. \\n\\nI also need to consider the attrCarrier; if it's not serializable, that could be problematic. It seems important that the readObject method handles everything properly during deserialization.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring compatibility issues**\\n\\nI might encounter an \\\"incompatible class\\\" issue if the local class name doesn't match the stream class name since it resolves based on the stream name. It’s important to know that ObjectStreamClass computes serialVersionUID, especially for a proxy with no fields, but we need to set it explicitly. Having a private static final long for the serialVersionUID field seems like a good idea. This might help ensure everything lines up correctly during serialization!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Checking testing guidelines**\\n\\nI need to follow the guideline that says \\\"Do not compile or run tests myself,\\\" which makes sense. Instead of running tests, maybe I could read the dynamic coverage JSON to see the mapping, but I'm not sure if that's necessary. I could also check for formatting issues like lines that are too long; I can use awk to check the line length for that. Keeping things in check is important!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_LtSaGUJbKzZxCTeRpXELcMfZ|fc_0d5bda6b5469ec1c0169fbf7f7ce4c8191a1453f1f4bcfcf02", "name": "ba